more recommended for people who already know how to play swordsoul as this is a harder to play list

So my first deck profile for this year is gonna be Ancient Warriors. Never thought I'd hear about them again...Anyways, this deck is named after the video game franchise "Dynasty Warriors", because both of them are inspired by the <em>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</em> historical novel.

&nbsp;

Anyway, this deck uses two new support cards revealed in Dimension Force. Tyrannical Dong Ying can search a Spell/Trap, or a Level 7 or higher Ancient Warriors monster. Defying The Warlord's Demands lets you special summon an Ancient Warriors monster, then burns you for 100 Life Points x that monster's Level.

&nbsp;

This deck can either go first or second. If you're going first, your goal is either to end on Double Dragons, Dong Ying, and Lu Feng for at least 2 disruptions. If you're going second, your goal is to summon as many big beaters into you can and pummel your opponent into submission.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

PUNKRUFFIA ORIGINALBUILD (Jan 2022)

&nbsp;

the Deck is all about summon [<a data-name="End punisher">End punisher</a>] using Psychic cards then use the Ruffia traps to be lower then opponent, afterwards its a GG since End punisher is unaffected by anything if he has LP lower then the opponent

<a>https://ibb.co/Wpc6sxd</a>

&nbsp;

Fur Hire spells are basically extenders, so aren't always necessary.

Verte Anaconda effect works even after using Sekka's Light.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

GLHF

this deck is for a homebrew format i'm working on called Vanguard format.

&nbsp;

The main gist of this homebrew format is that you start with a designated non-effect main deck monster on the board (either a normal monster or non-effect ritual monster) that cannot be tributed, cannot attack the opponent directly, cannot be used as the cost of another card's effect, cannot be turned face down, can't be taken control of, can switch between attack and defense position and takes damage in both attack and defense position. The concept is somewhat borrowed from Cardfight! Vanguard in that its a monster that remains on the board at all times and represents the player.

&nbsp;

This is designed to be a multi-man format (akin to Commander in MTG), hence why i have cards like The Forceful Sentry and Painful Choice allowed despite otherwise being banned in the OCG and TCG since i feel like they do a good job of encouraging negotiations between different players since you have to first designate which opponent you'll use a card's effect on in 3+ man games.

&nbsp;

When selecting the monsters for your main deck, you can only pick monsters that share either the same attribute and/or the same monster type as your vanguard. For example, i can put any dark and/or cyberse monsters in the main deck because Suppression Collider is a dark cyberse monster.

21 monsters and 21 spells, perfectly balancead.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

GLHF

&nbsp;

<a data-name="Dinorphia Rexsturm">Dinorphia Rexsturm</a> is really strong! Its the win conditon that the archtype needed!

I putted a Dogmatika engine here because the deck is slow, weak at going second and because Dogmatika have some interesting interactions with dinos.

One card combo: <a data-name="Dinorphia Frenzy">Dinorphia Frenzy</a>.

At the start of your opponent main phase- Activate Frenzy (4000LP) ~Fusion summon <a data-name="Dinorphia Kentregina">Dinorphia Kentregina</a> using 1 Dinorphia monster from your extra deck and another from you main deck ~Chain Kentregina quick effect to copy Frenzy effect (2000LP) ~Fusion summon Rexsturm using 1 Dinorphia from the extra deck and 1 from the main deck ~Now in the next time you activate a Dinorphia effect your life will be 1000,500 and so on, also <a data-name="Rexsturm">Rexsturm</a> will be negating passively almost all your opponent monster effects (to negate <a data-name="Verte Anaconda">Verte Anaconda</a> you gonna need at lest one more Dinorphia effect). Keep im mind that <a data-name="Rexsturm">Rexsturm</a> also has a quick effect to make your opponent monsters atk equal your LP, so having less LP is aways a win=win.

You can summon <a data-name="Ultimate Conductor Tyranno">Ultimate Conductor Tyranno</a> in the first turn using <a data-name="Dogmatika Maximus">Dogmatika Maximus</a> effect to send 2 dinosaurs from your extra deck to the gy. Aka <a data-name="Nadir Servant">Nadir Servant</a>+<a data-name="Ultimate Conductor Tyranno">Ultimate Conductor Tyranno</a>.

&nbsp;

Notes:

Floodgates dont work is this deck, except maybe for <a data-name="Summon Limit">Summon Limit</a>, but that just slows the deck even more.

<a data-name="Imperial Order">Imperial Order</a>, <a data-name="Extinction on Schedule">Extinction on Schedule</a><a data-name="Extinction Schedule">,</a> <a data-name="Solemn Strike">Solemn Strike and other traps with burn effects</a> aren't worth using. Just no kill yourself.

After reaching 1 LP you will stop losing LP from your divisions but the effect of them still can be used. This also means that is impossible to <a data-name="Rexsturm">Rexsturm</a> to negate 0 atk monsters.

<a data-name="Performage Damage Juggler">Performage Damage Juggler</a> is good to not let you die to battle or effect damage. <a data-name="Performage Hat Trick">Performage Hat Trick</a> can be used against burn decks or if you need to xyz summon when going second.

If you're scared or don't know how to play around of <a data-name="Dark Ruler No More">Dark Ruler No More</a>, <a data-name="Forbidden Chalice">Forbidden Chalice</a> or <a data-name="Forbidden Droplet">Forbidden Droplet</a> you can add second copie of Dinorphia Sonic.

&nbsp;

!Uptadate: i forgot adding <a data-name="Dogmatika Punishment">Dogmatika Punishment</a> xD but now the deck have 41 cards ;-;

!Update2: just to clarify somethings. 1-i am not using <a data-name="Dinorphia Stealthbegia">Dinorphia Stealthbegia </a>because from my experience it is useless to less 2-i am not using <a data-name="Dinorphia Reversion">Dinorphia Reversion</a> because it can be just a brick sometimes and don't have a effect so good in my opinion, same for <a data-name="Dinorphia Shell">Dinorphia Shell</a>.

&nbsp;

Happy new year!

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

GLHF

Fusion :)

&nbsp;

But a hand of Gamma + Scythe + any Fluffal name is an almost 100% guarantee that you'll be able to use Gamma twice in the game. Gamma to negate an effect, Scythe to go into Cruel Whale, and then Cruel Whale pop Driver and an opponent's card. The deck isn't meta at all, but it's so much fun to play. You can push for a huge OTK during turns 2-4, but you're most likely gonna struggle beyond that.

&nbsp;

I don't think there's any really spicy tech options here, but the art for the Fluffals is very cute :)

The deck is pretty standard, nothing super crazy or out there. I feel like D-Barrier is a good option, especially with Swordsoul and Drytron kicking around right now. Floowandereeze is definitely a tough matchup though.

&nbsp;

I don't really think that 3 copies of Secret Village is the way to go, but running the Terraforming to search it is essentially 3 copies, and can thin your deck just a little bit. I also find that Strike, while a really good card, can be too detrimental in the late-game. I know that's a sign of a bad Geist player, so feel free to flame me.

&nbsp;

Lastly, I find that the Extra Deck monsters can be really helpful in the late game, especially if you can get to Hexstia pointing to Memorygant, so I run 2 Extrav. This decision has actually never screwed me over, at least not yet. I just find that being able to keep some stuff in the ED can help when you start getting to the grind game.

&nbsp;

IO and Summon Limit in the Side because, I mean, ya gotta run floodgates if you wanna win. It sucks, but what can you do? I have the 3rd Extrav in the side because I needed one more card in there, and I felt like I could switch it out for the Terraforming if I really needed to.

&nbsp;

Mostly, I'm uploading this here to more easily check the TCG Player price, not gonna lie.
